“The sea is ours”: Bolivia, blocked, hopes that the court will reopen the way to the Pacific
Sailors patrolling an armoured boat at La Paz Naval Headquarters.
Public buildings have a blue flag like the ocean.
From Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, naval bases display the following bike: "The sea is ours.
Recovering it is a duty."
Throughout the blocked Bolivia, the memory of a coast lost to Chile during a conflict of bloody resources in the 19th century is still present. Just as the desire to navigate the Pacific Ocean, once again.
These hopes have not been so palpable for several decades, for Bolivia is waiting for a decision of the International Court of Justice, which will be delivered on 1 October, after five years of deliberations.
"Bolivia has the will, a spirit of unity and serenity, and of course expects a positive result," explains Roberto Calzadilla, Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will follow the decision of the International Court of Justice on a large screen throughout the country, hoping that the Hague Court will decide in favour of Bolivian demand. Bolivia hopes that, after decades of sporadic negotiations, Chile will have to negotiate the agreement on a sovereign passage to the ocean to Bolivia.
Evo Morales, the charismatic indigenous president of Bolivia (who is facing a controversial fight for re-election next year), also has a lot to say about the decision to be rendered on Monday.
"We are so close to returning to the Pacific Ocean," he said at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that there is little chance that the court will rule in favour of Chile, and that little would change, even in the event of a positive decision.
The United Nations body based in the Netherlands does not have the power to grant Chilean territory, and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of any talks.
The fact that the International Court of Justice renders its decision six months after the last arguments shows that the case “was not complicated,” explains Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And far from promoting Bolivia's cause, the last four years may have even harmed it.
"The problem of access to the sea has been diverted by the current Bolivian administration," said Zárate.
Morales' bellicose rhetoric undermined all the Chilean goodwill that remained, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to exchange views, but after that it will be very difficult to organize talks.
The last exchange of ambassadors between the two countries took place in 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, who represents Bolivia in the Hague, rejected the idea that the Court's decision-making was abnormally fast.
Monday will give Bolivia "an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile" and a chance to "end 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits," he said.
Calzadilla also challenged the fact that Morales - who remains to date one of the most popular presidents in Latin America - used the maritime problem as a political crutch.
"Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific Ocean," he added.
"The Court's decision is an opportunity to see that we must get rid of the past."
