John Edward: Language skills are essential to the world's citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a record of academic excellence.This trend continued in 2018 with new excellent exam results reinforced by collective and individual success in sports, art, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to provide the best level of service to students and their parents.
Independent schools work to prepare their students for higher education, the career they have chosen and their place as citizens of the world.
As an education sector capable of designing and implementing a tailor-made curriculum, we see that contemporary languages remain popular and desired subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you speak to him.
If you speak to him in his language, you speak to his heart."
This reminds us that we cannot rely on English to build relationships and build trust with people from other countries.
Looking at the excellent exam results this year, we see that languages are at the top of the ranking, with the highest success rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 per cent of students who studied foreign languages received the highest rating, A.
The data collected from the 74 SCIS member schools show that 72% of pupils achieved the highest grade, A, in Mandarin, as did the 72% of pupils who studied German, the 69% of pupils who studied French and the 63% of pupils who studied Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as an absolutely essential skill for children and young people in the future.
From now on, languages as subjects are organized as well as science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curricula of independent schools and other schools.
A survey carried out by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 reveals that 17% of employers' difficulties in recruiting candidates are linked to insufficient language skills.
Language skills are therefore increasingly vital for preparing young people for their future careers.
With more job opportunities requiring languages, these skills are essential in our globalized world.
Regardless of their career choice, a person who speaks a second language will have a real advantage in the future through this enduring skill.
Being able to communicate directly with foreigners will automatically place the multilingual person in front of its competitors.
According to a YouGov survey carried out in 2013 among 4000 adults living in the UK, 75% of them did not have enough foreign language to hold a conversation. French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage (15%).
That is why investing in language learning is important for children today.
By speaking several languages, including those of emerging economies, children will benefit from a better chance of finding a rewarding job.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Several of them will focus on contemporary classical languages, while others will teach languages considered important for the UK in the run-up to 2020, including Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's preferences, several languages will be available in independent schools, with specialist staff in the field.
Scottish independent schools want to provide a learning environment that will prepare children and give them the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds for them.
It is clear that, in a global trading environment, languages remain of vital importance to the country's future and must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be considered as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
We have to do it.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
