China reported a 14 per cent increase in the number of people living with HIV and AIDS.
According to the Chinese health authorities, more than 820,000 people are affected.
Nearly 40,000 new cases were reported in the second quarter of 2018.
Most patients have been infected during sexual intercourse, which is a new development.
Historically, the virus has spread rapidly in some parts of the country as a result of transfusions of contaminated blood.
However, the number of people infected with HIV in this way was almost zero, said the Chinese health authorities at a conference in Yunnan province.
However, from year to year, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000.
In the Chinese LGBT community, transmission of HIV through sexual intercourse is a serious problem.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against the LGBT community remains widespread.
Because of the conservative values of the country, studies estimate that 70 to 90 per cent of homosexual men end up marrying a woman.
Many cases of transmission are due to inadequate sexual protection.
As part of its efforts to combat this problem, the Chinese Government has promised universal access to HIV medicines since 2003.
