What is the Global Citizen Festival and did it do to reduce poverty?
This Saturday, New York will host the Global Citizen Festival, an annual musical event with a very impressive list of stars and an equally impressive mission: to put an end to poverty in the world.
The Global Citizen Festival, now in its seventh edition, will see tens of thousands of people rush to the Great Lawn in Central Park to not only benefit from the performance of artists such as Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to raise awareness of the festival's real goal of ending extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, the first edition of which took place in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international advocacy group that hopes to eradicate poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
In order to receive a free ticket for the event (unless you are willing to pay a VIP ticket), spectators had to do a series of tasks, or "actions", such as volunteering, email a world leader, phone or make any other useful effort to raise public awareness of the fight against poverty.
But to what extent can the Global Citizen organization still achieve its goal in the remaining twelve years?
Does the idea of rewarding people with a free concert really persuade them to demand a call for action, or is it just another example of "clicktivism" - a situation in which people really think of making a difference by signing a petition or sending a tweet?
Since 2011, Global Citizen has recorded more than 19 million "actions" from its supporters, who advocate for many different goals.
According to the organization, these actions have helped to encourage world leaders to make commitments and adopt policies amounting to more than $37 billion that are expected to change the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
In early 2018, the group mentioned 390 commitments and announcements arising from its shares, of which a tranche of at least $10 billion has already been disbursed or raised.
The group estimates that the guaranteed funds have so far had a direct impact on nearly 649 million people around the world.
Key commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a British partnership of investors and implementers who have committed themselves to "helping children develop their full potential," while promising Rwanda Pound35 million to help put an end to malnutrition in Rwanda after receiving more than 4,700 messages from Global Citizens.
"Thanks to the support of the British government, donors, national governments and Global Citizens like you, we can make the social injustice of undernutrition a footnote in history," said Tracey Ullman, an ambassador for The Power of Nutrition at a concert in London in April 2018.
The group also stated that following the undertaking of more than 5,000 actions to ask the United Kingdom to improve the nutrition of mothers and children, the government announced funding for a project, The Power of Nutrition, which will benefit 5 million women and children in nutrition interventions.
In response to one of the most frequently asked questions on its website, "what makes you think it is possible to end extreme poverty?"
Global Citizen said: "The way to it will be long and difficult, sometimes we will fall and fail.
However, like the major civil rights and anti-apartheid movements before us, we will succeed, because we are more powerful together.
