World Wide Web inventor plans to launch New Internet to challenge Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a brand new company that seeks to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest technology legend project, Inrupt, is a company that takes advantage of Berners-Lee's free platform.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored as well as people who are allowed to access such information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that Inrupt aimed at "dominating the world."
"We have to do it now," he said about the launch.
"It's a historical moment."
The application uses Solid's technology to allow people to create their own "personal data store online" or DPL.
It may contain contact lists, task lists, a calendar, a music library and other personal and professional tools.
It's as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify were all available at the same time on a single browser.
The particularity of the online personal data store is that it is entirely up to the user to decide who can access what type of information.
The company calls this "personal responsibility via data".
According to the CEO of the company, John Bruce, Inrupt's idea is that the company brings appropriate resources, processes and skills to make Solid accessible to all.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, a few developers working on a contract on the project and a community of volunteer coders.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world will be able to create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not yet in discussion with "Facebook and Google" to find out whether to make a complete change where all their business models are completely upset in an instant.
"We don't ask them for permission."
In an article published on Saturday on Medium, Berners-Lee writes that the "mission [of Inrupt] is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem in order to protect the integrity and quality of the new web built on Solid".
In 1994, at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet by creating the World Wide Web Consortium.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate on network neutrality.
Although he launched Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I am extremely optimistic about this new era on the web," added Berners-Lee.
