According to the London Gazatte, on September 29, 1918, Lieutenant-Colonel Vann directed his battalion on the Saint-Quentin Canal "through a very thick fog and under the violent firing of field guns and machine guns."
Later, he rushed to the line of fire and, with "greater bravery," guided the line before blowing a field cannon to himself and knocking three soldiers out of the detachment.
On October 4, 1918, a German sniper killed Lieutenant-Colonel Vann, just over a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said that his grandfather's actions were "a thing that I will never be, but that makes me humble."
He and his brother, Dr.James Vann, also laid a crown after the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band parade.
Michael Vann said he felt "very honoured to be part of the parade" and added that "the courage of an authentic hero is reflected in the support that will be given to him by many people."
